<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <p xml:id="MM7-intro">ēḻāvatu maṇimēkalā teyvam uvavaṉam pukuntu cutamatiyait tuyil eḻuppiyapāṭṭu.</p>
      <p xml:lang="en">The seventh song, in which Maṇimēkalā Teyvam, having entered the pleasure-grove, awakens Cutamati from sleep.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p type="edition"/>
      <p type="translation" xml:lang="en"> 
      </p>
    </div>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MM7">
<l>maṇimē kalaitaṉai maṇipal lavattiṭai</l>
<l>maṇimē kalāteyvam vaittu nīṅki</l>
<l>maṇimē kalaitaṉai malarppoḻiṟ kaṇṭa</l>
<l>vutaya kumara ṉuṟutuya reytik</l>
<l>kaṅkul kaḻiyileṉ kaiyakat tāḷeṉap</l>
<l>poṅkumel lamaḷiyiṟ poruntā tiruntōṉ</l>
<l>muṉṉart tōṉṟi maṉṉavaṉ makaṉē</l>
<l>kōṉilai tirintiṭiṟ kōḷ nilai tiriyuṅ</l>
<l>kōṇilai tirintiṭiṉ mārivaṟaṅ kūru</l>
<l>mārivaṟaṅ kūriṉ maṉṉuyi rillai</l>
<l>maṉṉuyi rellā maṇṇāḷ vēntaṉ</l>
<l>ṟaṉṉuyi reṉṉun takutiyiṉ ṟākun</l>
<l>tavattiṟam pūṇṭō ṭaṉmēl vaitta</l>
<l>vavattiṟa moḻikeṉ ṟavaṉvayi ṉuraittapiṉ</l>
<l>uvavaṉam pukuntāṅ kuṟutuyil koḷḷuñ</l>
<l>cutamati taṉṉait tuyiliṭai nīkki</l>
<l>yintira kōṭaṇai yinnakark kāṇa</l>
<l>vantē ṉañcaṉ maṇimē kalaiyā</l>
<l>ṉāticāṉ muṉiva ṉaṟavaḻip paṭūu</l>
<l>mētu mutirnta tiḷaṅkoṭik kātaliṉ</l>
<l>viñcaiyiṟ peyarttuniṉ viḷaṅkiḻai taṉṉaiyōr</l>
<l>vañcamiṉ maṇipal lavattiṭai vaittēṉ</l>
<l>paṇṭaip piṟappum paṇpuṟa vuṇarntīṅ</l>
<l>kiṉṟēḻ nāḷi linnakar maruṅkē</l>
<l>vantu tōṉṟu maṭakkoṭi nallāḷ</l>
<l>kaḷippumāṇ celvak kāvaṟ pērū</l>
<l>roḷitturu veytiṉu muṉṟiṟa moḷiyā</l>
<l>ḷāṅkava ḷinnakar pukunta vannā</l>
<l>ḷīṅku nikaḻvaṉa vētup palavuḷa</l>
<l>mātavi taṉakkiyāṉ vanta vaṇṇamu</l>
<l>mētami ṉeṟimaka ḷeytiya vaṇṇamu</l>
<l>muraiyāy nīyava ḷeṉṟiṟa muṇarun</l>
<l>tiraiyirum pauvattut teyvamoṉ ṟuṇṭeṉak</l>
<l>kōvalaṉ kūṟiyik koṭiyiṭai taṉṉaiyeṉ</l>
<l>ṉāmañ ceyta naṉṉā ṇaḷḷiruṭ</l>
<l>kāmaṉ kaiyaṟak kaṭunavai yaṟukku</l>
<l>māperun tavakkoṭi yīṉṟaṉai yeṉṟē</l>
<l>naṉavē pōlak kaṉavakat turaittē</l>
<l>ṉīṅkiv vaṇṇa māṅkavaṭ kuraiyeṉ</l>
<l>ṟantarat teḻuntāṅ karunteyvam pōyapiṉ</l>
<l>ventuya reytic cutamati yeḻuntāṅ</l>
<l>kakaṉmaṉai yaraṅkat tāciriyar tammoṭu</l>
<l>vakaiteri mākkaṭku vaṭṭaṇai kāṭṭi</l>
<l>yāṭal puṇarkku maraṅkiyaṉ makaḷiriṟ</l>
<l>kūṭiya kuyiluvak karuvikaṇ ṭuyiṉṟu</l>
<l>paṇṇukkiḷai payirum paṇṇiyāḻt tīntoṭai</l>
<l>koḷaival lāyamō ṭicaikūṭ ṭuṇṭu</l>
<l>vaḷaicēr ceṅkai melvira lutaitta</l>
<l>vemmaivey tuṟātu taṉmaiyiṟ ṟiriyavum</l>
<l>paṇpil kātalaṉ parattamai nōṉā</l>
<l>tuṇkaṇ civantāṅ kolkukoṭi pōṉṟu</l>
<l>teruṭṭavun teruḷā tūṭalōṭu tuyilvōr</l>
<l>viraippūm paḷḷi vīḻtuṇai taḻuvavun</l>
<l>taḷarnaṭai yāyamoṭu taṅkā tōṭi</l>
<l>viḷaiyāṭu ciṟutē rīrttumey varunti</l>
<l>yamaḷit tuñcu maimpaṭait tālik</l>
<l>kutalaic cevvāyk kuṟunaṭaip putalvarkkuk</l>
<l>kāvaṟ peṇṭir kaṭippakai yeṟintu</l>
<l>tūpaṅ kāṭṭit tūṅkutuyil vatiyavu</l>
<l>miṟaiyuṟai puṟavu niṟainīrp puḷḷuṅ</l>
<l>kāvuṟai paṟavaiyu nāvuḷ ḷaḻunti</l>
<l>viḻavukkaḷi yaṭaṅki muḻavukkaṇ ṭuyiṉṟu</l>
<l>paḻaviṟaṉ mūtūr pāyalko ṇaṭunāḷ</l>
<l>kōmakaṉ kōyiṟ kuṟunīrk kaṉṉaliṉ</l>
<l>yāmaṅ koḷpava rēttoli yaravamu</l>
<l>muṟaiyuṇiṉ ṟoṭuṅkiya vuṇṇā vuyakkattu</l>
<l>niṟaiyaḻi yāṉai neṭuṅkū viḷiyun</l>
<l>tērvaḻaṅku teruvuñ ciṟṟiṭai muṭukkaru</l>
<l>mūrkāp pāḷa reṟituṭi yōtaiyu</l>
<l>muḻaṅkunīr muṉṟuṟaik kalampuṇar kammiyar</l>
<l>tuḻantaṭu kaḷḷiṉ ṟōppiyuṇ ṭayarntu</l>
<l>paḻañceruk kuṟṟa vaṉantarp pāṇiyu</l>
<l>maravāyk kaṭippakai yaiyavik kaṭippakai</l>
<l>viraviya makaḷi rēntiya tūmattup</l>
<l>putalvaraip payanta puṉiṟutīr kayakkan</l>
<l>tīrviṉai makaḷir kuḷaṉā ṭaravamum</l>
<l>valitta neñci ṉāṭava riṉṟiyum</l>
<l>pulikkaṇat taṉṉōr pūta catukkattuk</l>
<l>koṭittēr vēntaṉ koṟṟaṅ koḷkeṉa</l>
<l>viṭikkuraṉ muḻakkat tiṭumpali yōtaiyu</l>
<l>mīṟṟiḷam peṇṭi rāṟṟāp pālakar</l>
<l>kaṭuñcūṉ makaḷir neṭumpu ṇuṟṟōr</l>
<l>tantuyar keṭukku mantira mākkaṇ</l>
<l>maṉṟap pēymakaḷ vantukaik koḷkeṉa</l>
<l>niṉṟeṟi paliyi ṉeṭuṅkura lōtaiyum</l>
<l>palvē ṟōtaiyum parantoruṅ kicaippa</l>
<l>kēṭṭuḷaṅ kalaṅki yūṭṭiru ḷaḻuvattu</l>
<l>muruntē riḷanakai nīṅkip pūmpoḻiṟ</l>
<l>ṟirunteyiṟ kuṭapāṟ ciṟupuḻai pōki</l>
<l>mikkamā teyvam viyanteṭut turaitta</l>
<l>cakkara vāḷak kōṭṭat tāṅkaṭ</l>
<l>palarpukat tiṟanta pakuvāy vāyi</l>
<l>lulaka vaṟaviyi ṉorupuṭai yiruttalum</l>
<l>kantuṭai neṭunilaik kāraṇaṅ kāṭṭiya</l>
<l>vanti leḻutiya vaṟputap pāvai</l>
<l>maittaṭaṅ kaṇṇāṇ mayaṅkiṉaḷ veruvat</l>
<l>tippiya muraikkun teyvak kiḷaviyi</l>
<l>ṉiravi vaṉma ṉoruperu makaḷē</l>
<l>turakat tāṉait tuccayaṉ ṟēvi</l>
<l>tayaṅkiṇark kōtait tārai cāvuṟa</l>
<l>mayaṅki yāṉaimuṉ maṉṉuyir nīttōy</l>
<l>kārāḷar caṇpaiyiṟ kaucikaṉ makaḷē</l>
<l>māruta vēkaṉō ṭinnakar pukuntu</l>
<l>tārai tavvai taṉṉoṭu kūṭiya</l>
<l>vīrai yākiya cutamati kēḷā</l>
<l>yiṉṟēḻ nāḷi liṭaiyiruḷ yāmattut</l>
<l>taṉpiṟap pataṉoṭu niṉpiṟap puṇarntīṅ</l>
<l>kilakkumi yākiya niṉakkiḷai yāḷvaru</l>
<l>mañcaleṉ ṟuraitta tavvurai kēṭṭu</l>
<l>neñca naṭukkuṟūum nēriḻai nallāḷ</l>
<l>kāva lāḷar kaṇṭuyil koḷḷat</l>
<l>tūmeṉ cēkkait tuyilkaṇ viḻippa</l>
<l>valampuric caṅkam vaṟiteḻun tārppap</l>
<l>pulampuric caṅkam poruḷoṭu muḻaṅkap</l>
<l>pukarmuka vāraṇa neṭuṅkū viḷippap</l>
<l>poṟimayir vāraṇaṅ kuṟuṅkū viḷippap</l>
<l>paṇainilaip puravi palaveḻun tālap</l>
<l>paṇainilaip puḷḷum palaveḻun tālap</l>
<l>pūmpoḻi lārkaip puḷḷoli ciṟappap</l>
<l>pūṅkoṭi yārkaip puḷḷoli ciṟappak</l>
<l>kaṭavuṭ pīṭikaip pūppali kaṭaikoḷak</l>
<l>kalampakar pīṭikaip pūppali kaṭaikoḷak</l>
<l>kuyiluvar kaṭaitoṟum paṇṇiyam paranteḻak</l>
<l>koṭuppōr kaṭaitoṟum paṇṇiyam paranteḻa</l>
<l>vūrtuyi leṭuppa vuravunī raḻuvattuk</l>
<l>kāriruḷ cīttuk katiravaṉ muḷaittalum</l>
<l>ēvuṟu maññaiyi ṉiṉaintaṭi varunta</l>
<l>mānakar vīti maruṅkiṟ pōkip</l>
<l>pōya kaṅkuliṟ pukuntatai yellā</l>
<l>mātavi taṉakku vaḻuviṉ ṟuraittalu</l>
<l>naṉmaṇi yiḻanta nākam pōṉṟava</l>
<l>ṭaṉmakaḷ vārāt taṉittuya ruḻappa</l>
<l>viṉṉuyi riḻanta yākkaiyi ṉiruntaṉa</l>
<l>ṭuṉṉiya turaitta cutamati tāṉeṉ</l>
</lg>
<lg xml:lang="en">
<l corresp="1-2">The deity Maṇimēkalā, having put Maṇimēkalai on [the island of] Maṇipallavam, and left, </l>
<l corresp="7ab">[and] appeared in front of </l>
<l corresp="3-4">Utayakumaraṉ, who had seen Maṇimēkalā in the flower grove, [deep-]felt sorrow having reached [him]/having attained [deep-]felt sorrow, </l>
<l corresp="5">[and was] thinking, 'When the night ends, I'll have her in [the palm of] my hand'</l>
<l corresp="6">being one who sat [up], not going to [his] bed which was as soft as the foaming [sea], </l>
<l corresp="7cd">[said], 'O son of the king! </l>
<l corresp="8">If the [king's] sceptre wavers in [its] position, the planets will swerve from [their] course. </l>
<l corresp="9">If the planets swerve from [their] course, there will be excessive drought/drought will increase. </l>
<l corresp="10">If there is excessive drought, there will be no lasting life/living beings will cease to be.</l>
<l corresp="11-12">The king who rules the earth will become unworthy to call all living beings his own (lit. his life). </l>
<l corresp="13-14ab">The harmful path that you have adopted towards her who has undertaken the path of penance: may it cease!' </l>
<l corresp="14cd">After speaking thus to (lit. on/over) him – </l>
<l corresp="15-16">  [Maṇimēkalā Teyvam], having entered the pleasure-garden [and] snatched Cutamati, who was taking [deeply-] felt sleep there, from the midst of sleep, said: </l>
<l corresp="17">'In order to see [the festival] of the thunder of Indra in this city, </l>
<l corresp="18">I came. Fear not! I, Maṇimēkalai– </l>
<l corresp="20">because for the young creeper the hetu (reason) has ripened, </l>
<l corresp="19">[the reason] that put [her] on the path of dharma [laid down] by the primeval, supreme sage (the Buddha) – </l>
<l corresp="21">having taken away your [girl with] shining jewels by magic, </l>
<l corresp="22">have set her down, without a single deceit, on the island of Maṇipallavam. </l>
<l corresp="23">Having realised all [her] previous birth(s)–in a way that the qualities [of her previous births] will have been felt–</l>
<l corresp="25">the good, artless creeper will come and appear here, </l>
<l corresp="24">seven days from today, in this city – </l>
<l corresp="26">great city, of prosperous guard, glorious/famous for its joyfulness/intoxication/bustle/this joyful, glorious, prosperous, [well]-guarded and great city; </l>
<l corresp="27">even though she will reach [here] in disguise (lit. having concealed [her true] form), she will not hide [her true] nature [from] you. </l>
<l corresp="28">On that day when that girl enters this city there, </l>
<l corresp="29">the hetu that shine/occur here will be many. </l>
<l corresp="30">To Mātavi, the way in which I came, </l>
<l corresp="31">and the way in which her daughter took to the faultless path, </l>
<l corresp="32">tell! She knows my nature/history/ methods/affairs/reasons. </l>
<l corresp="34-35">On the good day at midnight (lit. in the middle of darkness) when Kōvalaṉ gave (lit. made) my name to this creeper-waisted [girl], declaring/asserting [to Mātavi]: </l>
<l corresp="33">"There is one deity in the depths of the big/dark waves,"</l>
<l corresp="38">I told [Kōvalaṉ or Mātavi or both] in a dream, [which seemed] as though [he were] awake, </l>
<l corresp="37">that, "You have begotten a creeper of very great austerity </l>
<l corresp="36">who will cut away fierce faults, so that Kāma will be rendered impotent."</l>
<l corresp="39">Tell to (i.e. remind, since she already knows) that woman there [Mātavi] these matters here!' so saying, </l>
<l corresp="40">there the rare deity [Maṇimēkalā Teyvam] rose up into the aether and left; after she had left – </l>
<l corresp="41">Cutamati, having reached [a state of] fierce sorrow, [and] having got up there (i.e. in the uvavaṉam);</l>
<l corresp="45">the eye of the assembled/united instruments which are the delight of the Koel bird (i.e.flute, yāḻ, and drums - UVS - has to be drum here because of the ref to the eye) having fallen asleep; </l>
<l corresp="44">like/together with the dancing girls of the dancing hall/stage, who bring the dance together</l>
<l corresp="43">by showing the kamala-vārttaṉai gesture to the people who know/understand/are conoisseurs of [all the different] types [of dance-gestures], </l>
<l corresp="42">together with [their] [dance and music] teachers in the dancing hall(s) of the wide house(s); </l>
<l corresp="46">The sweet strings of the yāḻ's notes which sound the [different] note branches, </l>
<l corresp="47">having enjoyed - better to take as pass aux. 'the strings having been combined' combining musical-sounds with the band (i.e. the other instruments) which is skilled in melodies/keeping time, </l>
<l corresp="48">while [the female players'] red hands heaped with bangles </l>
<l corresp="49">wander according to [their] nature, not feeling the hot heat which strikes [their] soft fingers; </l>
<l corresp="52">[and] while those [women] who go to sleep with/despite jealous-sulking, not noticing as [their husbands] try to pacify [them], </l>
<l corresp="50">being unable to bear [their] worthless husbands' consorting with other women, </l>
<l corresp="51">resembling weak creepers there, [their] collyrium-[lined] eyes having reddened,</l>
<l corresp="53">embrace [their] husbands who fall [with them]/their beloved husbands [on] beds of fragrant flowers; </l>
<l corresp="58">while the nannies (lit. watch-women) – having scattered Margosa plant (as protection against evil spirits), </l>
<l corresp="57">for the toddling sons (lit. of short gait) with pratlling red mouths, </l>
<l corresp="56">sleeping [in their] beds, [with] aimpaṭaittāli [round their necks], </l>
<l corresp="54">after not staying with the weak legged group [of nannies] (lit. slack-gait-group), running [away], </l>
<l corresp="55">pulling [their] little toy chariots, [and] hurting themselves –</l>
<l corresp="59">having waved the incense [over the children] (lit. shown i.e. to god), stay in sleepy sleep; </l>
<l corresp="60-61">the tongues of pigeons who nest in the eaves [of houses], and of birds of the ample water, and of birds who live in the groves having been pressed inside [their mouths] (i.e. silenced);</l>
<l corresp="62">the intoxication/hilarity having come to an end; the eyes of the drums having fallen asleep; </l>
<l corresp="63">at midnight when the ancient city, victorious of old, was taking to [its] bed /taking rest. </l>
<l corresp="65">The incantatory murmuring sound of the time keepers' praising [the king]/proclaiming [the hour]</l>
<l corresp="64">by means of the little water pot at the king's palace; </l>
<l corresp="67">and the frenzied-sound of an elephant's long cry for help as it suffers fully, </l>
<l corresp="66">because of the agony of starvation, [an elephant] who has been captured and is standing inside a stall; </l>
<l corresp="69">and the sound of the Tuṭi-drums beaten by the city watchmen </l>
<l corresp="68">on both the streets where chariots roam and the narrow lanes; </l>
<l corresp="72">and the drinking songs experienced because of the intoxication by fruit [alcohol]</l>
<l corresp="70">of artisans who have assembled on [their] boats at the front ghat by the thundering waters [of the ocean]</l>
<l corresp="71">having engaged in drinking tōppi toddy, which they have brewed by stirring; </l>
<l corresp="76">and the confused-sound of bathing in the pond by women whose labour is over, </l>
<l corresp="75">whose stress of recent delivery is over, [women] who have given birth to sons (or perhaps children?)</l>
<l corresp="74">[using] incense held up by the women, who mixed </l>
<l corresp="73">snake-mouth [neem - or could this refer to a plant that protects from snake bites] kaṭippakai [and] white-mustard kaṭippakai;</l>
<l corresp="80">and the sound of offerings being placed with clamour of thunderous voices </l>
<l corresp="79">saying, 'May [our] king with bannered chariots achieve victory!' </l>
<l corresp="78">at the crossroads [haunted by] bhūta, [voices] of men resembling packs of tigers, </l>
<l corresp="77">for the sake of the elimination of men (i.e. enemy warriors) with hearts compelled [to fight]; </l>
<l corresp="85">and the long[-drawn out] sound of the voices of people throwing offerings, as they stand/constantly throwing (adv. niṉṟu), </l>
<l corresp="83">[people who recite] mantras/spells to get rid of the suffering </l>
<l corresp="84">saying, 'Let the pēy come to the common and take up [their offerings]!' </l>
<l corresp="82">[the suffering] of those who have experienced a long[-lasting]/long in length wound: women with a fierce/ first pregnancy,</l>
<l corresp="81">young women who have given/are giving birth, [and] helpless/disabled babies; </l>
<l corresp="86">all the many different sounds spread and reverberated together. </l>
<l corresp="87">[Cutamati], having heard [the above sounds, and] having become perturbed at heart, in the depths of the [all-]suffusing darkness—</l>
<l corresp="88">[her] young sprout-like smile having left [her]—</l>
<l corresp="89">[and] having gone [from] the flower grove by the little bowered walk-way through overhanging trees [which led along] the western side of the perfect fortress</l>
<l corresp="91">to Cakkaravāḷakkōṭṭam there—</l>
<l corresp="90">which she had been told about by the very great deity [Maṇimēkalā]—[and] having extolled and raised [Cakkaravāḷakkōṭṭam] up,</l>
<l corresp="93">[she] sat down to one side of the World Assembly, </l>
<l corresp="92">[which has] a portal with split doors that are opened for many people to enter. </l>




</lg>  
